Preliminary Analysis & Pre-processing

(Imbalance Case)

> kaggle_credictcard %>% 
+   group_by(Class) %>% 
+   tally %>% 
+   mutate(prop = n/(sum(n))) -> tmp
> highchart() %>%
+   hc_title(text = "Fraud Proportion") %>%
+   hc_subtitle(text = "Fraud is extremly less") %>% 
+   hc_add_series_labels_values(labels = tmp$Class, values = tmp$n,
+                               name = "Bar", type = "pie")

sample_frac kaggle_credictcard_no_dup 70% train setdiff (kaggle_credictcard_no_dup Train ) test Time and Amount 

> train <- sample_frac(kaggle_credictcard_no_dup, 0.7)
> test <- setdiff(kaggle_credictcard_no_dup, train)
> # check 
> # (nrow(train) + nrow(test)) == nrow(kaggle_credictcard_no_dup)
> # drop columns 
> train %<>% select(-Time, -Amount)
> test %<>% select(-Time, -Amount)

R ROCR AUC 0.98

> pr <- prediction(pred$posterior[,2], test$Class)
> auc_slot <- performance(pr,"auc") # ?performace  measure 
> auc <- unlist(slot(auc_slot, "y.values"))
> auc %>% round(3)
[1] 0.979

ROC Curve 

> perf <- performance(pr,"tpr","fpr")
> plot(perf)

AUC Kaggle AUPRC (Area Under Precision-Recall Curve) ROC PRC AUPRC R

When dealing with highly skewed datasets, Precision-Recall(PR) curves give a more informative picture of an algorithms performance

prcbench AUPRC

ROC prediction pr.curve Positive Positive Positive Positive 

> library("PRROC")
> lda.fit <- lda(Class ~ ., data = train)
> pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test, type = "response")
